05360nam a22008775i 9783110702859DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107028597 a10.1515/97831107028592doi  a(DE-B1597)549683  a(OCoLC)1206395467  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aBD201b.T43 2021 4aBD201b.T43 2021  aCI 50172rvk0(DE-625)rvk/18463:116161 aTechio, Jônadas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Threat of Solipsism :bWittgenstein and Cavell on Meaning, Skepticism, and Finitude /cJônadas Techio. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (XIV, 210 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBerlin Studies in Knowledge Research ;v1600tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Solipsism and the limits of sense in the Tractatus Logico- Philosophicus -- t2. Solipsism and method in the Philosophical Remarks -- t3. Solipsism, privacy, and the grammar of the first person in The Blue Book -- t4. The threat of privacy in the Philosophical Investigations: Cavell and Kripke on skepticism about meaning -- t5. Seeing souls: Wittgenstein and Cavell on skepticism about other minds -- t6. Taking skepticism seriously: Stroud and Cavell -- t7. Skepticism, perfectionism, and the limits of morality -- tReferences -- tIndex of subjects -- tIndex of names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMuch attention has been paid to Wittgenstein’s treatment of solipsism and to Cavell’s treatment of skepticism. But comparatively little has been made of the striking connections between the early Wittgenstein’s view on the truth of solipsism and Cavell’s view on the truth of skepticism, and how that relates to the claim that the later Wittgenstein sees privacy as a constant human possibility. This book offers close readings of representative writings by both authors and argues that an adequate understanding of solipsism and skepticism requires taking into account a set of underlying difficulties related to a disappointment with finitude which might ultimately lead to the threat of solipsism. That threat is further interpreted as a wish not to bear the burden of having to constantly negotiate and nurture the fragile connections with the world and others which are the conditions of possibility for finite beings to achieve meaning and community. By presenting Wittgenstein’s and Cavell’s responses in an order which reflects the chronology of their writings, the result is a cohesive articulation of some under-appreciated aspects of their philosophical methodologies which has the potential of reorienting our entire reading of their work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aSkepticism. 0aSolipsism. 4aCavell, Stanley. 4aSkeptizismus. 4aSolipsismus. 4aWittgenstein, Ludwig.  aCavell, Stanley.  aScepticism.  aWittgenstein, Ludwig.  asolipsism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package 2021z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020 Englishz978311070482208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020z9783110704648oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831107028800 cprintz978311070265140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311070285940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110702859423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110702